{{Infobox scientist | name = Paul-Gilbert Langevin | birth_date = {{birth date|1933|7|5|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Boulogne-Billancourt]], France | death_date = {{death date and age|df=y|1986|7|4|1933|7|5}} | death_place = [[Paris]], France | residence = France | field = [[Musicology]], [[classical music]], [[symphonic music]], [[physical chemistry]] | work_institution = [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]], [[Université Pierre-et-Marie-Curie]], Anton Bruckner french society | education = [[ESPCI]], [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]], Centre Universitaire de Vincennes }}
'''Paul-Gilbert Langevin''' ([[Boulogne-Billancourt]], 5 July 1933 – [[Paris]], 4 July 1986) was a French musicologist, who wrote books on [[Anton Bruckner]], [[Franz Schubert]] and 19th-century classical music.
Paul-Gilbert Langevin was the son of French physicist [[Paul Langevin]] (1872–1946)<ref name="Langevin1977p4">{{cite book|last=Langevin|first=Paul-Gilbert|title=Anton Bruckner, apogée de la symphonie|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fhUzi81BbBEC&pg=PP4|year=1977|publisher=l'Âge d'Homme|page=4|via=Google Books}}</ref> and [[Eliane Montel]] (1898–1992), a private teacher at the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]] science department. He started his scientific education at the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]] and then completed it at the [[Pierre and Marie Curie University|Université Pierre-et-Marie-Curie]], obtaining a degree in [[physical chemistry]] under the supervision of professor René Freymann<ref>[https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF03161964 ''The scientific life and work of René Freymann (1909–1995)''], on Springer website.</ref>.
From a young age, Langevin had a deep interest in classical music, listening to [[Anton Bruckner]]'s symphonies on radio recordings during his youth and meeting conductor [[Roberto Benzi]].<ref>[http://www.robertobenzi.com/ Conductor Roberto Benzi], personal website.</ref> Having completed his scientific degrees, he decided to write a thesis under the supervision of [[Daniel Charles]] at the ''Centre Universitaire de Vincennes'' about 19th century Austrian music, focusing on composer [[Anton Bruckner]] and the so-called "ethnoromantic" period<ref>{{cite book|last=Langevin|first=Paul-Gilbert|title=Musiciens d'Europe|url=http://ressources.ircam.fr/record/default:UNIMARC:28890|year=1986|publisher=La Revue Musicale|via=IRCAM website}}</ref>.
He became a physics teacher at the Sorbonne science department, and then, at the [[Université Pierre-et-Marie-Curie]], which was created in the 1960s. During this time, he met musicologists [[Harry Halbreich]], Gustave Kars, Jacques Feschotte, [[Pierre Vidal (composer)|Pierre Vidal]], [[Marc Vignal]] and [[Jean-Luc Caron]]. Langevin went on to create the Anton Bruckner French society,<ref>[https://www.cairn.info/revue-reliance-2007-2-page-140.htm ''Anton Bruckner, ce pauvre sot''], paper by Alfred and Françoise Brauner, on ''Cairn'' website.</ref> wrote books on 19th-century symphonic music, edited in ''La Revue Musicale'' and ''L'Age d'Homme'',<ref name="Langevin1977p3">{{cite book|last=Langevin|first=Paul-Gilbert|title=Anton Bruckner, apogée de la symphonie|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fhUzi81BbBEC&pg=PA3|year=1977|publisher=l'Âge d'Homme|page=3|via=Google Books}}</ref> and became a music critic in ''Le Monde de la Musique'', edited by Anne Rey.
From the 1950s, Langevin focused on classical music, symphonic music, and writing. Specifically, he wrote articles, monographs and books about Anton Bruckner, [[Franz Schubert]], [[Guillaume Lekeu]], [[Albéric Magnard]], [[Joseph-Guy Ropartz]] and [[Charles Koechlin]]. He was also interested in works by [[Hugo Wolf]], [[Gustav Mahler]], [[Arnold Schoenberg]], [[Franz Schmidt]], [[Ferruccio Busoni]],<ref>[http://www.rodoni.ch/busoni/opere/LANGEVIN.html ''Ferruccio Busoni et son oeuvre symphonique''], paper by Paul-Gilbert Langevin, on ''rodoni.ch'' website.</ref> [[Leoš Janáček]] and [[Carl Nielsen]].
He died on 4 July 1986.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}
